0

Description

The TA505 threat group targeted the banking sector with spear-phishing emails that contained a malicious attachment and installed the FlawedAmmyy remote access trojan. The RAT was used to drop an email stealer to harvest credentials from multiple software applications.

B1txor20 Backdoor Spreading Via Log4j Vulnerability

0

0

Never

Description

The B1txor20 botnet targets Linux devices and conceals command and control communication using DNS tunneling. The malicious software can perform a range of tasks including arbitrary command execution, exfiltrating sensitive data, downloading additional malware, and installing a SOCKS5 proxy, backdoor or rootkit. B1txor20 targets Linux platforms with ARM and X64 CPU architectures and gains access by exploiting the Log4J vulnerability.

The Trellix ATR Team gathers and analyzes information from multiple open and closed sources before disseminating intelligence reports. This campaign was researched by 360 Netlab and shared publicly https://blog.netlab.360.com/b1txor20-use-of-dns-tunneling_cn/

PcShare Backdoor Attacks

0

0

Never

Description

Tropic Trooper, also known as KeyBoy, targeted the technology sector in Southeast Asia with the PcShare backdoor. The threat actor also replaced the Microsoft Windows Narrator “Ease of Access” feature with a malicious application allowing the group full control over the infected system.

COVID-19 Vaccine Development Targeted

0

0

Never

Description

The APT29 threat group, also known as Cozy Bear, targeted a range of sectors across Canada, Great Britain, and the United States. The campaign focused on entities involved in COVID-19 vaccine development including the government, diplomacy, think-tank, healthcare, and energy domains. The cyber espionage group used malware labeled WellMess, WellMail, and SoreFang to steal sensitive data, install malicious software, execute shell commands, and run scripts. APT29 used spear-phishing emails and exploited public facing servers to carry out the initial infection vector.

SockDetour Backdoor Targets U.S. Defense Contractors

0

0

Never

Description

Threat actors are targeting the technology, energy, healthcare, education, finance, and defense sectors with a custom backdoor known as SockDetour. The malicious software is used as a backup backdoor in case the primary backdoor is compromised or detected. The campaign focuses on exploiting flaws in multiple applications including an improper authorization vulnerability in QNAP NAS classified under CVE-2021-28799.

The Trellix ATR Team gathers and analyzes information from multiple open and closed sources before disseminating intelligence reports. This campaign was researched by Palo Alto Networks and shared publicly https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/sockdetour/
